1
00:00:02,670 --> 00:00:04,570
NARRATOR: Marshall and Marvin
were taking the bus

2
00:00:04,605 --> 00:00:07,175
on their way to Long Island
to meet up with us.

3
00:00:07,208 --> 00:00:08,578
(crying)
There, there,
little Marvin.

4
00:00:08,609 --> 00:00:10,179
Let no more
tears fall.

5
00:00:10,211 --> 00:00:13,851
We're gonna see Mommy
in no time at all.

6
00:00:13,881 --> 00:00:16,081
Hello there. I'm sorry
for all of the noise.

7
00:00:16,117 --> 00:00:18,217
It's been a long day
for the Eriksen boys.

8
00:00:18,252 --> 00:00:20,392
Uh... what's with the rhyming?

9
00:00:20,421 --> 00:00:21,761
I'm glad that you ask.

10
00:00:21,789 --> 00:00:24,729
To get my son
sleeping is no easy task.

11
00:00:24,758 --> 00:00:27,098
A few weeks ago,
the job fell to my wife.

12
00:00:27,128 --> 00:00:29,758
And as the poor baby cried out
for dear life,

13
00:00:29,797 --> 00:00:32,997
she read every book,
but all were no use

14
00:00:33,033 --> 00:00:36,173
until she arrived
at a mother named Goose.

15
00:00:36,204 --> 00:00:38,174
Why, Marvin...
MARSHALL:
She noted.

16
00:00:38,206 --> 00:00:40,006
...these rhymes
make you tired!

17
00:00:40,040 --> 00:00:42,080
And ever since then,
all young Marvin's required

18
00:00:42,110 --> 00:00:44,350
is one book of rhymes,
and to dream land he goes.

19
00:00:44,378 --> 00:00:45,948
Now, what shall we read?

20
00:00:45,979 --> 00:00:48,419
Oh, crap, I left
his book in the car!

21
00:00:48,449 --> 00:00:50,179
(crying)

22
00:00:50,218 --> 00:00:51,518
That blows.

23
00:00:51,552 --> 00:00:53,222
(crying stops)

24
00:01:06,234 --> 00:01:07,974
Oh, no, what a bummer!

25
00:01:08,001 --> 00:01:09,471
What craptastic luck!

26
00:01:09,503 --> 00:01:12,043
Without Marvin's rhyme book,
this ride's gonna suck!

27
00:01:12,072 --> 00:01:14,042
Does anyone here have
some poetry maybe?

28
00:01:14,074 --> 00:01:15,084
Or any advice?
Yeah!

29
00:01:15,109 --> 00:01:16,779
Don't have a baby!

30
00:01:16,810 --> 00:01:18,710
(laughter)

31
00:01:18,746 --> 00:01:20,646
I guess if I don't want
young Marvin to wake up,

32
00:01:20,681 --> 00:01:23,421
the rhymes will just have
to be ones that I make up.

33
00:01:23,451 --> 00:01:26,451
I'll whip up some poetry
in seconds flat!

34
00:01:29,623 --> 00:01:32,493
Oh, I know!

35
00:01:32,526 --> 00:01:34,996
This story's called
Mosby at the Bat!

36
00:01:40,368 --> 00:01:42,968
The outlook wasn't brilliant
for poor Ted's romantic life.

37
00:01:43,003 --> 00:01:46,973
He was deep into his thirties,
and yet, still he had no wife.

38
00:01:47,007 --> 00:01:48,637
But then, one day
whilst grading papers,

39
00:01:48,676 --> 00:01:50,136
life sent him a whammy.

40
00:01:50,178 --> 00:01:52,178
A physics prof named Lisa

41
00:01:52,213 --> 00:01:53,583
who'd just moved here
from Miami.

42
00:01:53,614 --> 00:01:54,784
Professor?

43
00:01:54,815 --> 00:01:56,475
She asked timidly.
He answered:

44
00:01:56,517 --> 00:01:58,087
Call me Ted.
Oh.

45
00:01:58,118 --> 00:01:59,418
I don't want to bother you.

46
00:01:59,453 --> 00:02:00,923
Please, have a seat.
He said.

47
00:02:00,954 --> 00:02:04,464
I'm fairly new to teaching,
and I'm looking for advice.

48
00:02:04,492 --> 00:02:07,662
Every night I practice giving
lectures, sometimes twice.

49
00:02:07,695 --> 00:02:08,955
But when I teach

50
00:02:08,996 --> 00:02:12,126
magnetic force,
I just see eyeballs glazing.

51
00:02:12,166 --> 00:02:17,536
I asked around, and people say
your lectures are amazing.

52
00:02:17,571 --> 00:02:18,941
Which is really
saying something,

53
00:02:18,972 --> 00:02:20,972
because, architecture? Yawn.

54
00:02:21,008 --> 00:02:22,938
And Ted thought...

55
00:02:22,976 --> 00:02:25,176
TED: Psh, yeah, 'cause physics
is so interesting.

56
00:02:25,213 --> 00:02:26,553
Go on.

57
00:02:26,580 --> 00:02:28,120
It's just
that you're so skilled,

58
00:02:28,148 --> 00:02:29,948
and I'm a relative beginner.

59
00:02:29,983 --> 00:02:33,953
If it isn't too much trouble,
can I take you out to dinner?

60
00:02:33,987 --> 00:02:37,557
I'd love to get some pointers,
and I shouldn't keep you late.

61
00:02:37,591 --> 00:02:39,161
What do you say?

62
00:02:39,193 --> 00:02:40,563
What do I say?

63
00:02:40,594 --> 00:02:42,304
Teddy Westside's
got a date!

64
00:02:42,330 --> 00:02:44,230
ALL: Hooray!
MARSHALL: We cheered.

65
00:02:44,265 --> 00:02:45,295
Ted's off the bench!

66
00:02:45,333 --> 00:02:46,803
Our boy's back in the game!

67
00:02:46,834 --> 00:02:48,344
Thank God, it's been
a hundred years

68
00:02:48,369 --> 00:02:49,699
since Mosby scored a dame.

69
00:02:49,737 --> 00:02:51,567
The last time he saw
boobies was

70
00:02:51,605 --> 00:02:52,965
the screen-test
scene in Fame.

71
00:02:53,006 --> 00:02:54,236
The last girl he dated,

72
00:02:54,275 --> 00:02:56,135
I think "Righty" was her name.

73
00:02:56,176 --> 00:02:57,976
Hold it.
Let's not all go crazy

74
00:02:58,011 --> 00:02:59,851
like some wild berzerkers.

75
00:02:59,880 --> 00:03:02,680
What if this is just a business
meal between co-workers?

76
00:03:02,716 --> 00:03:04,716
MARSHALL: Ted thought back
on past failed dates.

77
00:03:04,752 --> 00:03:06,852
Oh, God, that
could be true.

78
00:03:06,887 --> 00:03:10,057
How many times have I come
home to find my balls are blue?

79
00:03:10,090 --> 00:03:13,230
It all depends where Ted and
his new fetching young Floridian

80
00:03:13,261 --> 00:03:16,101
are standing in relation
to that puzzling meridian

81
00:03:16,129 --> 00:03:18,099
called
"The International Date Line."

82
00:03:18,131 --> 00:03:19,601
That's right, new theory.

83
00:03:19,633 --> 00:03:21,673
"What's that," you ask?
Nobody did.

84
00:03:21,702 --> 00:03:24,172
I'll now address your query!
The date line

85
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:27,344
is the border betwixt happiness
and sorrow.

86
00:03:27,375 --> 00:03:29,605
On this side,
you go home tonight.

87
00:03:29,643 --> 00:03:32,613
On this side, home tomorrow.

88
00:03:32,646 --> 00:03:36,176
MARSHALL:
And then, as Barney made some
gestures that were rather rude,

89
00:03:36,216 --> 00:03:39,116
Ted left to go meet Lisa,
in a rather puzzled mood.

90
00:03:39,152 --> 00:03:41,052
Was this a date?

91
00:03:41,088 --> 00:03:42,918
He simply couldn't tell
how he was faring.

92
00:03:42,956 --> 00:03:44,056
Then Lisa showed up.

93
00:03:44,091 --> 00:03:47,561
Ted rejoiced to see
what she was wearing.

94
00:03:47,595 --> 00:03:48,955
For girls at business dinners

95
00:03:48,996 --> 00:03:51,056
don't have necklines
that revealing!

96
00:03:55,336 --> 00:03:58,406
But then a friendly handshake
gave poor Ted

97
00:03:58,439 --> 00:03:59,969
a sinking feeling.

98
00:04:04,578 --> 00:04:06,048
And so, the night wore on.

99
00:04:06,079 --> 00:04:08,279
And back and forth,
the globe rotated.

100
00:04:08,316 --> 00:04:11,946
But still, Ted's curiosity was
never fully sated.

101
00:04:11,985 --> 00:04:13,415
How long could this continue?

102
00:04:13,454 --> 00:04:15,294
He was truly fortune's pawn.

103
00:04:15,323 --> 00:04:17,293
Then Lisa saw the TV.

104
00:04:17,325 --> 00:04:18,925
Hey, the Yankees game is on!

105
00:04:18,959 --> 00:04:20,629
Of baseball...
Ted observed...

106
00:04:20,661 --> 00:04:23,561
...you seem to have some
firsthand knowledge.

107
00:04:23,597 --> 00:04:25,227
To which the lady shrugged
and said...

108
00:04:25,265 --> 00:04:26,765
I played softball in college.

109
00:04:29,803 --> 00:04:31,513
Now the age-old softball
stereotype's just that,

110
00:04:31,539 --> 00:04:33,139
and nothing more.

111
00:04:33,173 --> 00:04:34,643
Yeah!
But as the Yankees got a run,

112
00:04:34,675 --> 00:04:36,835
Ted feared he wouldn't score.

113
00:04:36,877 --> 00:04:38,607
For while the date side
of the line's

114
00:04:38,646 --> 00:04:40,846
the one we all might guess
he's in,

115
00:04:40,881 --> 00:04:43,481
there'll be no joy in Tedville
if our Lisa is a...

116
00:04:43,517 --> 00:04:45,117
Yes! We win!

117
00:04:45,152 --> 00:04:47,462
Then Lisa took a drink
and said...

118
00:04:47,488 --> 00:04:49,518
This may sound kind of random,

119
00:04:49,557 --> 00:04:52,187
but there actually is a reason
for my rabid Yankee fandom.

120
00:04:52,225 --> 00:04:54,155
I guess I'll just be
honest here,

121
00:04:54,194 --> 00:04:56,004
though crazy it may seem.

122
00:04:56,029 --> 00:05:00,199
My first week in New York,
I dated someone on the team.

123
00:05:00,233 --> 00:05:01,443
Which player?

124
00:05:01,469 --> 00:05:02,969
I'm not saying.
Please?

125
00:05:03,003 --> 00:05:04,443
What are you, a reporter?

126
00:05:04,472 --> 00:05:06,012
Ted's mind began to race.

127
00:05:06,039 --> 00:05:07,639
The waiter came
to take their order.

128
00:05:07,675 --> 00:05:09,035
As Lisa said...

129
00:05:09,076 --> 00:05:11,006
I might like
the spaghetti marinara.

130
00:05:11,044 --> 00:05:12,554
Poor Ted just wondered
silently...

131
00:05:12,580 --> 00:05:15,150
TED:
Mariano Rivera?

132
00:05:15,182 --> 00:05:16,152
MARSHALL:
And as she said...

133
00:05:16,183 --> 00:05:18,323
I read this place has great
chicken Milano.

134
00:05:18,352 --> 00:05:20,552
All Ted could bring himself
to think was:

135
00:05:20,588 --> 00:05:22,488
TED:
Alfonso Soriano?

136
00:05:22,523 --> 00:05:24,023
I want something hearty.

137
00:05:24,057 --> 00:05:26,327
How about blackened miso cod?

138
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:27,560
TED:
Is it Joe Girardi?

139
00:05:27,595 --> 00:05:30,025
Holy crap, is it A-Rod?!

140
00:05:30,063 --> 00:05:31,633
Okay, Ted, calm down.

141
00:05:31,665 --> 00:05:33,165
You've got
to get yourself together.

142
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:34,900
Just smile, be charming,

143
00:05:34,935 --> 00:05:37,065
ooze charisma,
talk about the weather.

144
00:05:37,104 --> 00:05:38,544
For this might be a date,

145
00:05:38,572 --> 00:05:40,812
which means there might be
hanky-panky.

146
00:05:40,841 --> 00:05:44,141
So, dude, be cool, relax,
don't even...

147
00:05:44,177 --> 00:05:45,847
Just tell me which Yankee!

148
00:05:47,347 --> 00:05:49,477
I'd rather not
discuss this here.

149
00:05:49,517 --> 00:05:51,317
But then again, I'd hate...

150
00:05:51,351 --> 00:05:54,391
to let a silly secret ruin
such a lovely date.

151
00:05:54,422 --> 00:05:55,862
If there's

152
00:05:55,889 --> 00:05:57,059
an elephant in the room,

153
00:05:57,090 --> 00:05:58,090
why don't we just remove it?

154
00:05:58,125 --> 00:05:59,425
I dated Derek Jeter.

155
00:05:59,460 --> 00:06:01,030
Here's a picture
that'll prove it.

156
00:06:01,061 --> 00:06:03,261
MARSHALL:
As Ted looked
at that cell phone pic,

157
00:06:03,296 --> 00:06:05,026
there were two things
he reckoned.

158
00:06:05,065 --> 00:06:07,025
This definitely was a date,

159
00:06:07,067 --> 00:06:09,567
but there wouldn't be a second.

160
00:06:10,638 --> 00:06:11,908
See? It worked.

161
00:06:11,939 --> 00:06:13,909
I said some rhymes,
and out my boy did conk.

162
00:06:14,708 --> 00:06:16,278
Now let's enjoy the ride.

163
00:06:16,309 --> 00:06:17,279
(brakes screech)

164
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:19,080
Move, jackass!
(honk)

165
00:06:19,112 --> 00:06:21,282
(crying)

166
00:06:25,218 --> 00:06:27,588
Okay, I need a brand-new tale
to silence Marvin's chatter.

167
00:06:27,621 --> 00:06:30,591
I don't know, that last one had
some sketchy subject matter.

168
00:06:30,624 --> 00:06:33,734
Forgive me, but before you got
here, did you smoke a joint?

169
00:06:33,761 --> 00:06:36,101
You don't tell kids a tale
that crass!

170
00:06:36,129 --> 00:06:37,529
NARRATOR:
I guess he had a point.

171
00:06:37,565 --> 00:06:39,765
I know, I said some things
that were,

172
00:06:39,800 --> 00:06:41,900
as you say,
kind of questionable.

173
00:06:41,935 --> 00:06:43,965
The truth is,
children Marvin's age

174
00:06:44,004 --> 00:06:45,774
aren't really
that impressionable.

175
00:06:45,806 --> 00:06:48,206
Do you remember anything
from when you were this small?

176
00:06:48,241 --> 00:06:51,311
Pumpkin picking at age three is
the first thing I recall.

177
00:06:51,344 --> 00:06:52,654
Hmm.
Huh.

178
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:53,950
He won't remember this.
I guess it's true.

179
00:06:53,981 --> 00:06:55,221
It better be.

180
00:06:55,248 --> 00:06:56,478
Or else we'll end up paying

181
00:06:56,517 --> 00:06:58,117
through the nose
for Marvin's therapy.

182
00:06:58,151 --> 00:07:00,991
Okay, buddy, nice chat,
but I think I need a break.

183
00:07:01,021 --> 00:07:01,961
Great idea.

184
00:07:01,989 --> 00:07:04,089
After this story!

185
00:07:04,124 --> 00:07:05,764
Robin Takes the Cake.

186
00:07:11,164 --> 00:07:13,134
Once in an East Side bakery,

187
00:07:13,166 --> 00:07:16,136
your debonair Aunt Robin was
making other customers think,

188
00:07:16,169 --> 00:07:18,139
"Geez, who let this slob in?"

189
00:07:18,171 --> 00:07:21,071
She didn't care about their
stares, or who was looking on.

190
00:07:21,108 --> 00:07:22,508
She'd just broke up with...

191
00:07:22,543 --> 00:07:23,783
Kevin.

192
00:07:23,811 --> 00:07:26,211
No, Gael. Or Scooby?

193
00:07:27,648 --> 00:07:29,148
Don?

194
00:07:29,983 --> 00:07:30,983
Now, sometimes,

195
00:07:31,018 --> 00:07:32,318
when it rains it pours,

196
00:07:32,352 --> 00:07:33,652
and sometimes,
it starts snowing,

197
00:07:33,687 --> 00:07:36,157
for as cream filling
hit her shirt...

198
00:07:36,189 --> 00:07:37,589
MAN:
Hey, Robin, how's it going?

199
00:07:37,625 --> 00:07:39,525
'Twas Simon, her ex-boyfriend

200
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:42,000
from her younger days
in Canada,

201
00:07:42,029 --> 00:07:43,529
but now, he looked
quite different...

202
00:07:43,564 --> 00:07:46,134
Um...

203
00:07:46,166 --> 00:07:47,366
Rhyme.

204
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:49,970
Uh... thinking. Uh...

205
00:07:50,003 --> 00:07:52,373
I've just been handed
a news flash.

206
00:07:52,405 --> 00:07:53,965
The word "Canada"
is unrhymeable.

207
00:07:54,007 --> 00:07:55,607
It's easier to--
I don't know--

208
00:07:55,643 --> 00:07:57,553
get drunk and try
to climb a bull.

209
00:07:57,578 --> 00:08:00,008
But Canada, damn it,
ask any man on the planet

210
00:08:00,047 --> 00:08:01,347
and watch
their stammerin' stamina

211
00:08:01,381 --> 00:08:04,051
as they clamor and cram it
into the middle of a sentence

212
00:08:04,084 --> 00:08:05,554
for a shot at repentance,

213
00:08:05,586 --> 00:08:07,986
pass the problem on to all
their non-rhyming descendants.

214
00:08:08,021 --> 00:08:10,291
I've never met anyone who could
clean up after Canada.

215
00:08:10,323 --> 00:08:12,133
Except my Uncle Tony
from the Bronx.

216
00:08:12,159 --> 00:08:13,129
He's a janitor.

217
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:15,160
(applause)

218
00:08:17,197 --> 00:08:20,027
Show-off.

219
00:08:20,067 --> 00:08:22,037
Simon. Nice to see you.

220
00:08:22,069 --> 00:08:24,169
So, what brings you to New York?

221
00:08:24,204 --> 00:08:25,574
I live here now.
What? Really?

222
00:08:25,606 --> 00:08:27,036
Yeah.
That's great.

223
00:08:27,074 --> 00:08:28,684
Can I get a fork?

224
00:08:28,709 --> 00:08:30,179
MARSHALL:
He'd always been a deadbeat

225
00:08:30,210 --> 00:08:31,910
and your classic hoser phony,

226
00:08:31,945 --> 00:08:34,875
but seeing Simon all cleaned up
hit Robin like a Zamboni.

227
00:08:34,915 --> 00:08:37,045
And as she looked him
up and down,

228
00:08:37,084 --> 00:08:38,394
young Robin felt a tingle.

229
00:08:38,418 --> 00:08:40,218
Had Simon blossomed finally?

230
00:08:40,253 --> 00:08:42,163
And if so, was he single?

231
00:08:42,189 --> 00:08:43,759
So great.

232
00:08:43,791 --> 00:08:46,031
She purred, whilst batting
her eyelashes like a flooze.

233
00:08:46,059 --> 00:08:48,159
Yup, I'm engaged
to Louise Marsh,

234
00:08:48,195 --> 00:08:50,025
and our pad's got a Jacuzz!

235
00:08:50,063 --> 00:08:52,233
The bakery spinned,
the floor dropped out.

236
00:08:52,265 --> 00:08:53,995
The air was thick as syrup.

237
00:08:54,034 --> 00:08:56,004
Poor Robin swooned,
she couldn't breathe,

238
00:08:56,036 --> 00:08:57,866
her eyes began to tear up.

239
00:08:57,905 --> 00:08:59,865
And as she tried
to stammer some excuse

240
00:08:59,907 --> 00:09:01,607
to get away, Simon said:

241
00:09:01,642 --> 00:09:04,082
Our wedding cake is
pretty bitchin', eh?

242
00:09:04,111 --> 00:09:07,511
And so was born the worst idea
poor Robin's ever had.

243
00:09:07,547 --> 00:09:10,047
And on Ted's door
there came a rapping.

244
00:09:10,083 --> 00:09:12,123
I did something bad.

245
00:09:12,152 --> 00:09:13,722
As Robin told her tale,

246
00:09:13,754 --> 00:09:15,864
Ted knew
she'd made a massive boo-boo.

247
00:09:15,889 --> 00:09:20,059
For stealing someone's wedding
cake is terribly bad juju.

248
00:09:20,093 --> 00:09:22,563
Robin, I'm beside myself
to see what you've become!

249
00:09:22,596 --> 00:09:24,426
You must return
this cake at once!

250
00:09:24,464 --> 00:09:25,434
I can't!
Why not?

251
00:09:25,465 --> 00:09:26,795
'Cause...

252
00:09:26,834 --> 00:09:28,274
Yum.

253
00:09:28,301 --> 00:09:32,411
Ted gasped, for he had never
seen a brazen act so vicious.

254
00:09:32,439 --> 00:09:34,209
Robin felt remorse, and yet...

